Text: Promises.  In the last (almost) 11 YEARS I have been either pregnant or breastfeeding for 8.5 of them.  8.5 YEARS of nourishing not only my body but another humans.  And let‚Äôs be honest it is great, but all good things come to an end am I right?? üòâ. Taking care of myself and being active has always been on the to-do list but not quite a priority.  A week ago I made a promise to myself to take care of me.  . Each day I hit my steps, workout, and sweat because I have promised myself. I love the dollar section at Target.  But let‚Äôs be honest if you go through that area of the store a child or two, or three, or four, is bound to walk away with something because ‚Äúit‚Äôs only a dollar.‚Äù In our amazon prime world a sense of entitlement is happening.  What is happening to manners?  Or having to be patient and wait for things. To save up money and EARN the things. . As a mother I start to wonder if I am raising grateful kids or entitled kids.... Appreciation vs. Entitlement.. Not that ever buying the kids something is bad at all.  I believe in sharing, showing love through gifts, and living a life of abundance.  BUT  am I buying it because it‚Äôs ‚Äúonly a dollar‚Äù and it‚Äôs cute, OR because it is truly needed?. Reading the book Raising Grateful Kids in an Entitled World by Kristen Welch is bringing important points to the forefront of my mind. . To love on the kids with quality time, but also when expressing love with things that those things aren‚Äôt replacing quality time.  Or replacing the guilt I feel because of a bad day. . While we are in a same day delivery world, we have to be careful of our perception.  Is entitlement or gratitude?  To love on our kids and give them all the things but to do it selflessly and for the right reasons.  Not to fill a void they have or we have with things.  . Instead filling up their love tanks with quality time, words of affirmation, acts of kindness, and hugs and snuggles.. #lovelanguages #time #randomthoughts #moms #gratitude

What is Let Me Run?. Let Me Run is a nonprofit wellness program that inspires boys to be themselves, be active, and belong. With a comprehensive curriculum that applies the power of running, the program encourages boys to develop their psychological, emotional and social health, in addition to their physical health. . Twice a week for seven weeks, two trained volunteer coaches lead an elementary or middle school team through practice. Designed to amplify confidence, self-expression, and respect for others, each practice includes a lesson from the Let Me Run curriculum that incorporates running, games and activities. Each fall and spring season culminates in a 5k race festival that celebrates the boys‚Äô personal growth.

Groundbreaking Study Proves Let Me Run Increases Social Competence and Fosters Healthy Masculinity.. A 2016 independent study conducted by University of North Carolina at Greensboro√¢¬Ä¬ôs Institute to Promote Athlete Health and Wellness finds Let Me Run is making a substantial positive impact in boys√¢¬Ä¬ô lives. A review of the professional literature revealed UNCG√¢¬Ä¬ôs groundbreaking study to be the first published to examine healthy masculinity in boys, as well as a program√¢¬Ä¬ôs ability to improve it.. Let Me Run seeks to break down negative societal pressures that require males to mask their authentic selves behind a performance of masculinity, in which the most praised emotions are anger, aggression and pride. Phrases like √¢¬Ä¬úman up,√¢¬Ä¬ù √¢¬Ä¬úboys don√¢¬Ä¬ôt cry√¢¬Ä¬ù and √¢¬Ä¬ústop being a girl√¢¬Ä¬ù serve as catalysts for this type of destructive macho-masculinity. As described by Dr. William Pollack in his book Real Boys, these unhealthy male stereotypes, which Pollack refers to as the √¢¬Ä¬úBoy Code,√¢¬Ä¬ù can stand in the way of boys√¢¬Ä¬ô positive futures and lead to disturbing consequences such as illness, decreased learning potential, addiction, and violence. These often unspoken issues lead ninety men in the U.S. to commit suicide every day, four of whom are boys under the age of 19.

My baby girl is all grown up. Eighteen years old! Where did the time go?. She is creative, her imagination as well as the way she processes things really astonishes me. I often wonder ''how did your head get from here to there?''. She is a fighter, my goodness is she a fighter!! She can''t stand injustice and wants to do something about it.. She is amazingly honest and authentic! Take her or leave her, this is who she is! She is an amazing woman and has grown into an astounding person, and I am so proud of her.

It sounds like manufacturers can no longer have channels on YouTube, as they are generally intending to sell guns. If someone makes an instructional safety video but also links to the manufacturer's webpage, it also seems like it would be banned. Photo of Flag Memorial to 9/11 fallen at ND from earlier today. . Today''s weather was similar to 2001. It made me remember seeing lots of students standing outside the dorms on their  cellphones where the reception was much better. With so many students from both coasts you knew that people were checking on family and loved ones. Others spontaneously gathered at the grotto. I remember helping my beloved boss and friend Dave Prentkowski hauling cases of bottled water for those that needed it as the day had warmed up quite a bit. And then we sat silently and listened to the priests and contemplated the sad events of that horrible day.

Number 5. I have worn through more copies of this than any other album. Even my mp3s are showing signs of wear.   Mom and Dad must have had second thoughts of buying me another Stones album for my birthday after the prior year‚Äôs Sticky Fingers because I had to pay for this double-album myself. Maybe that‚Äôs why it never left my turntable for six months. . Next nominee Keith Chrzan got to see the Stones in ‚Äò78

Up 2nd is Blood on the Tracks by Bob Dylan. I get that some people can‚Äôt get past the nasal gravelly voice. There are some artists I‚Äôll never get for the similar reasons. But for the initiated, this album of sadness and loss hits the base emotions of everyone. The regret of Tangled up in Blue and Simple Twist of Fate, the betrayal-induced raw anger of Idiot Wind, the wistful sad remorse of final departure in You‚Äôre Gonna Make Me Lonesome When You Go, the reality of impending imminent doom in Lily Rosemary and the Jack of Hearts. All the while with the minimal production and common lyric vernacular, Bob Dylan proves indeed ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs no actor anywhere better....‚Äù. Influential album No. 4 - The Who.  On a given day any of 4 albums.  The Who Sell Out - where they truly arrive with a fresh combination of songwriting, execution, style and wit.  Who''s Next - the perfect, classic sound from the first tones of synthesizer to that final most definitive scream of all of rock and roll.  Quadrophenia - maybe the best rock expression of teenage angst.  And Tommy if only for The Overture, The Underture and Keith Moon‚Äôs drumming. . In the spirit of Keith Moon I nominate Robert Kapiszka  He moved the library.  He avenged the snow bird.  He don‚Äôt need to be forgiven.

My friend Brenda Bradley has invited me to list the 10 most influential albums in my life. For 10 days I will list one, not in a particular order. I will start with The Beatles White Album though I suppose it should be number 9, number 9, etc. The photo is of my current vinyl copy, one of the original embossed and numbered versions lovingly given to me on a recent Fathers Day. . I have always felt it had a little bit of everything. Rocking Helter Skelter and Back in the USSR, the plaintive almost haunting Dear Prudence, the sonic soaring musicianship on While My Guitar Gently Weeps, Lennon‚Äôs painful ode to his mother Julia, a peek through Alice‚Äôs Looking Glass Onion in Cry Baby Cry, McCartney‚Äôs elegant social commentary of Blackbird.  And much, much more. The album I always reach back to. . I nominate my big cousin and earliest musical influencer Jim Furr . I remember as a youngster marveling at his fabulous collection and his tastes definitely rubbed off on me. Beatles, Beach Boys, Rolling Stones and others. Thanks, cuz.

This is a loving reminder to please get a mammogram once a year. Encourage all your love ones to get one. I am so thankful that I had one done on November 5th, because I knew it was a year since my last one.  Long story short they discovered a small mass on my left breast.  It was so small I could not feel it.  The needle biopsy confirmed that it is a slow growing cancer. On January 17th the mass will be removed. If the pathology report comes back the way we hope it means on radiation twice a day for 5 days. After the radiation I will be taking a pill once a day.  Do to this little bump in the road my knee replacement surgery that was supposed to be done on November 27th will not happen for a few months.  I am so thankful for all of the love, prayers and support from my family and friends.  Please make sure  you get a mammogram and remember men can also get breast cancer. Have a wonderful holiday season and may 2019 bring you happiness, love, peace and good health.  Love all of you.

My story for this month/week/year LOL. This morning, Cindy and I got up and cleaned out my 2003 Malibu to take it to a local dealership because I wanted a new car.. As we got close, we were sitting at a stop-light.  Suddenly WHAM!!! I was rear-ended.. Sigh......figures..going to trade in the ride and I get hit.  Cindy jumps out before I did and she''s already around to my side telling me I have no damage.  Guy is back there, I get out and we look - neither of us has any damage.  Really wasn''t anyone''s fault.  Roads were icy and he said he couldn''t get the car to stop despite the fact that he tried way back to stop - I get it - been there and got lucky that I didn''t bump anyone.. I look at the guy and he''s wearing a jacket of the dealership we were going to!  I ask if he works there (his name is also on the jacket so I''m guessing yes).  He does!  . I laughed and said we were just on our way there.. What kind of car are we going to look at?  I said either a Hyundai or Subaru - that''s where he works!!  So I told him we were going to get a Starbucks and we''d be over - I even offered to buy him a coffee (which he declined) - then we informed him he was going to be our salesman.. By the time we got there, everyone in the dealership was talking about how he rear-ended my car and ended up getting a customer.. Yeah I got a car - nice deal and everyone there was exceptionally nice.. *We''re both a little sore from the jolt but nothing bad.
Well at least the cats will enjoy it more :)

Also note this is Florida who just fucking elected Voldemort for another six years to the senate after spending 8 years destroying the state as governor ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è . ‚ÄúUsually I discuss or think about an issue before commenting. Instead, today, I am going to give you whatever my initial knee-jerk thoughts are. Here goes:.  . This is stupid. It''s a shotgun approach (see how many companies and, by extension, steps in the process are being targeted with this lawsuit). I have no love for any company that puts profit above patient care but this has been a tricky issue. . Did the pharmacies become aware something was wrong? Sure. But when? . Did they have the means to stop it? Possibly. But what steps could they have taken? Limit doses distributed to each pharmacy? . We didn''t have a PMP database in many states until quite recently. A National database? Nope. . Here is the biggest problem I have with the State of Florida. When patients are showing up in another state, approximately 2000-3000 miles away with prescriptions from pain clinics from your state (Georgia was just as guilty), how can you not recognise the problem resides in your state? It''s not the fault of the pharmacies for filling the prescriptions, at least not initially. . (Especially troubling is when your regular patients begin to see those prescribers. Are they turning into bad patients? or are they simply caught in the mix as the prescriber turns to the Dark Side? This requires vigilance on the part of the pharmacists but we know before anyone else who and where the bad prescribers are. And we report them.). The guiltiest party is the State of Florida itself. The most surprising part was the speed with which pain clinics were allowed to set up and flourish in the State of Florida. Pharmacists reported them and what did the state do? Nothing. It takes years to investigate and shut down a clinic such as these. (Which is mind-boggling in itself.) Licenses of the prescribers? Slaps on the wrists; many still allowed to practise. . . or they relocated. . Maybe this is just a distraction technique. Maybe, if the state goes after someone or, as in this case, everyone, the people will forget and ignore that the state is just as culpable in their citizens'' deaths as the prescribers who were allowed to set up shop and prescribe freely. . (Can I write another post showing how the pharmacies should/could share responsibility? Sure. But like I said, this is my initial reaction and I''m not writing a thesis today.) As I have long said, it''s really easy to point the finger at the end of the line because the further up the process you go, the more likely you''ll find yourself to blame. (Remember my Water Treatment Plant analogy? Yeah. This is so that.). New Headline: CVS, Walgreens sued by Florida after State allowed pain clinics to set up shop and kill its residents. #FixedIt‚Äù

When an immigrant is separated from his or her child, there‚Äôs a way to reunite that family that doesn‚Äôt require any action from Congress or the Trump administration: You pay an immigration bond, the parent is released from detention, and the children can then rejoin their parents. But the immigrants themselves rarely have the necessary cash. Immigration bonds are never less than $1,500 and are usually closer to $5,000, $10,000, or more. The bonds will, eventually, get repaid, once the immigrant‚Äôs case is heard. A bond is not a fine: It‚Äôs just a surety, designed to ensure that the immigrant shows up to all court dates. Once the immigrant has obtained legal status or has been deported, a process that can take well over a year, then the conditions of the bond are met, and the government gives the money back. A permanent bond fund, which has the resources to bail out every detained parent, and ideally every wrongfully detained immigrant, is a fantastic public good, and once it‚Äôs seeded with enough money, it can operate almost indefinitely..

I decided this morning that today was the day to finish War & Peace.  And I''m glad I did, not because Tolstoy offers a view of history that is hopeful or optimistic.  Nope. Tolstoy makes it very clear that he believes people will continue to harm each other for reasons that are beyond our understanding for the rest of time. Bad stuff happens and we have relatively little control over our lives.  . But he''s an artist, not a historian -- he reminds the reader of that fact repeatedly -- and he also urges the reader not to put their faith in so-called great men. They ain''t nothin.  Instead make the truth your hero.  And use love -- love for life, love for everyone -- as your guiding force.  . Tolstoy and I disagree on some things (i.e., women, just about anything he says about women), but he was a person who thought deeply and seriously about big things and it was a pleasure to spend to day with him.  . Up next for me: TBD palate-cleansing genre fiction and then Women, Race, and Class by Angela Y. Davis

Trigger warning: 9/11, war. I went to New York two weeks after 9/11 to visit a friend in Williamsburg, Brooklyn. I took the bus. Port Authority was as you‚Äôd imagine. Walls plastered with posters pleading for info about missing loved ones, the smiling faces at the center of each piece of cheap photocopy paper in stark contrast to the desperate message and the knowledge that they were all dead. Clusters of lit candles along the wall made the grimy bus terminal feel like a holy site.. I took the subway to Brooklyn. My friend and her roommates, all artists living in a warehouse illegally converted into apartments, talked about the way the air smelled. It smelled like smoke. It smelled like fuel. She opened a kitchen drawer and took out a stack of what looked like scrap paper. Every sheet had scorch marks. Some were just a little singed on the edge. Others had gaping holes. She thrust them at me. They floated across the river, she explained. The air smelled, she said, like burning paper. All those offices. Her eyes were wet. . We went to brunch. We talked about books. I was reading Turgenev‚Äôs Virgin Soil. She was reading Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire. A roommate was reading Gaddis. The conversation returned to 9/11. What would happen. Probably a War. I worried about people I knew who were in the military. Surely the war would be short. No, said the Gaddis reader, not short. Not contained. . Later that night we went dancing at some clubs and I lost a rain coat.

Listen. with the night falling we are saying thank you. we are stopping on the bridges to bow from the railings. we are running out of the glass rooms. with our mouths full of food to look at the sky. and say thank you. we are standing by the water thanking it. standing by the windows looking out. in our directions. back from a series of hospitals back from a mugging. after funerals we are saying thank you. after the news of the dead. whether or not we knew them we are saying thank you. over telephones we are saying thank you. in doorways and in the backs of cars and in elevators. remembering wars and the police at the door. and the beatings on stairs we are saying thank you. in the banks we are saying thank you. in the faces of the officials and the rich. and of all who will never change. we go on saying thank you thank you. with the animals dying around us. taking our feelings we are saying thank you. with the forests falling faster than the minutes. of our lives we are saying thank you. with the words going out like cells of a brain. with the cities growing over us. we are saying thank you faster and faster. with nobody listening we are saying thank you. thank you we are saying and waving. dark though it is

The twins are doing a project (for public school in CA) on biblical allusions in literature which requires them to understand 50 notable biblical stories, people, and things. For the past two weeks we have talked about biblical stuff almost every day thinking through any music, film, or literary reference to each of the stories. . I am an atheist...this is how most of the conversations went:. Kid: Who is Pontius Pilates?. Me: Pilates? Like the exercise? Um...I''m pretty sure that''s not in the bible.. Denis: Pilate. Kid: Pilot? That''s how you say it?. Me: Oh...is that the hand washing dude? Your sibling showed me a meme of that.
Watching election results while going over the process of calculating wavelength frequency and energy with the kids. I'd like to think they learned a little something about both.

Conversations on recent events with my very non-communicative son who has no interest in current events and who has said that he probably won''t vote when he grows up. (Parental and sibling nagging will continue on that!). Me: So Quinn, do you feel this is a dangerous time to be a young man in America?. Quinn (looking at me very confused): Why are you asking me this? What do you even mean by dangerous for young men? (Suspiciously) Did something happen? What happened now?. Me: The president said that it is a dangerous time to be a young man because of like fake sexual assault claims. As a young man, I thought I would ask you how you feel.. Quinn: Ok...there is literally nothing about what the president said that is true. Sighs...Like it''s not even close to accurate. That comment makes no sense. People aren''t worried about that. Why did he even say that? The opposite is true. *starts muttering about ridiculous people in the world for several minutes. My conclusion: This is not a concern for the average young man.

Two years ago today, a person whose heart was full of fear, shame, and hate walked into a gay club during Pride month and stole 49 of our family. I will never forget the way I felt that morning, waking to the news that something so horrendous had happened. I remember saying, now there''s nowhere we are safe, and at the time I truly believed it. I was lost in many ways then, and it was easier to lose hope than to rise up and refuse to be terrorized. Today, I''m a much different, stronger person and I am so proud of all of my LGBTQ family for continuing to be out and proud. We are not afraid, we are not ashamed, we do not hate. We embrace everyone with open arms and work day in and day out to make the world better for the future. We have a long way to go, but we have come so far. . There are tons of kids, mostly all living in motels with either their families, friends or foster families. These kids are applicable for every food assistance program available to them. Free lunches and all that jazz. Long story short, some friends of mine decided to start cooking hot meals and bringing them to these families. Nice, hot, home cooked meals. They had a picnic in the parking lot. It was beautiful, so they started to make it a regular thing.. Well, low and behold, the city finds out and wants to slap a $3000 fine for eating a meal with these families. They say there needs to be a commercial kitchen, blah blah blah. They wanna shut this shit down. ... *makes that one face* . I want ya√¢¬Ä¬ôll to shift your perspective for a second, because this is an incident of a widespread cultural shortcoming. When was the last time a commercial kitchen was required to feed your family and friends for a get-together? Fucking answer me that. When was the last time you grilled some burgers with your neighbor, and he was like, √¢¬Ä¬úShow me your permit.√¢¬Ä¬ù Is it illegal to feed each other at a block party? Nope. Is it illegal to bbq at a tailgate with your friends? Nope. Then it shouldn√¢¬Ä¬ôt be illegal to do what we do. What√¢¬Ä¬ôs the difference? That they√¢¬Ä¬ôre poor and hungry?√¢¬Ä¬ù

So this happened Wednesday, Nellie took it to the local news on Thursday night.  Overnight, after airing the story, the city of Belton reached out and is now saying that they won√¢¬Ä¬ôt fine anyone.  The process worked, but it shouldn√¢¬Ä¬ôt ever be an issue to consider.  No one should be threatens a fine for sharing a meal with someone else.

Luke 3 - 2 takeaways for me today:. 1. John is preaching reprentance and setting the stage for Jesus. May come to him asking what should they do:. * if you have 2 tunics, share with one who has none. * if you have food, do the likewise. * Tax collectors - collect no more than what is due. * Soldiers - do not extort money using false threats and accusations. Be content with your wages. So basically, we are to share, care for the poor and do what is honorable and right in our dealings with others. The chapter ends with the genealogy of Jesus, starting with him and going backwards. This is important as it demonstrates fulfillment of prophecy that Jesus was to come from the line of David. It also demonstrates to me that family matters. Understand your family tree and where you come from and the impact that has on your life. Someday, you will just be a name in the middle of your tree. What is the legacy you are leaving?

BEWARE - new kind of bank fraud called 'fostering'". You get a call from your bank saying there has been fraud on your account (Caller ID said USAA so they spoof their phone number). Everything looks legit, you get confirmation codes via text. Turns out, you are talking to a fraudster who has someone else with them who are spoofing YOU to your bank. So all of the validation emails, etc are legitimate, but they are coming due to actions the fraudster is trying to accomplish with your bank (move funds, initiate wire transfers etc). Learned this first hand today. Fortunately, I got suspicious and called the bank directly. They could see the outbound text messages, but the operator sending them was Elizabeth and I was talking to a DUDE. FRUSTRATED. USAA was able to stop all the transactions so no loss, other than time and account resets, etc. Valuable lesson. So - if your bank calls you unexpectedly, tell them you will call them back (USAA confirmed this is a best practice and not offensive). Ask for a name and extension. Make sure you are using a trusted phone number for your bank."

**WARNING Voting Post**. 3 ballots I''m very excited to be voting for in this year''s Colorado midterms. What issues are you passionate about?. Yes on Amendment 73 establishes tax brackets at 200k, 300k, and 500k, raise the corp rate (4.63% to 6%) for state income taxes and lower the property tax rates (residential: 7.2% to 7% and non-residential: 29% to 24%). The measure would also establish the Quality Public Education Fund to help fund K-12 schooling, a commonly overlooked area that is deserving of more public funding. . Yes on Amendment Y and Z, measures that would create an independent board (made up of an even representation of Dems, Reps, and unaffiliated totaling 12 members) in charge of drafting state legislative and U.S. federal congressional district lines.  Death to the 2 party system! . (Sorry 5ish) Yes on Proposition 110 (No on Prop 109), measure to authorize $6 billion in new government bonds to help fund transportation infrastructure improvements. In order to pay back the bonds, it would raise the state sales tax for 20 years to 3.52%. The critical piece here where it differs from Prod 109, is that this one authorizes the increase of sales tax, so that visitors and temporary residents can help fund our state and local roads. Prop 109 funds will only authorize bonds that will only impact state roads (leaving 88% of roads ineligible for funding). . Feel free to ask me more about my choices if you don''t know how to vote tomorrow. https://powactionfund.org/take-action/colorado/ is a great source of info regarding both sides of each measure and state/federal candidate. And please correct me if you see anything wrong in my reasoning, I have sources to back all these decisions from POW!. .

***Long Post if You Feel Like Being Inspired***. On my drive to work this morning I realized something drastic. How many of you at one time or another have felt like someone else was deciding who you are for you? The answer is everyone. We live in a world full of opinions. That being said, truly, the only person who can decide who you are and what you stand for, your good qualities, your bad qualities, the things you want to work on, the really great parts of you that make you YOU is...infact, YOU. I, probably am the most guilty of letting other peoples opinions of me become my truth. It''s a curse, seriously! Someone doesn''t agree with the way I operate, finds my humor offensive, decides I''m not worthy of their friendship, reminds me of my demons in the past --and these are just to name a few. Do you know what I''ve always done? I''ve held onto those words, the hate, the disagreements, the OPINIONS of others and I sort of tell myself that this is who I am, I punish me for being human instead of reminding myself that this life is so much more than someone elses opinion of me. What I''m trying to convey with this is----don''t ever let another person in your life determine the way you feel about you. It''s fine to take advice, it''s fine to learn new ways to communicate and to be the very best version of yourself that you can but please---do THAT for you, not for the person deciding you''re unworthy or for the people who think they know you, that truly don''t even have a clue. Stay true to yourself and love HARD. Don''t be afraid to mess up. How can we be loved by others and really appreciate all of the good in this world if we''re too busy hating on ourselves and wishing we were something that we''re not. This post is mostly for me. A big FAT reminder that I''m AWESOME and that so are all of you. If you have a roof over your head, food on your plate, a place to call home, family and friends----that right there is enough to say, you''re doing something right. Life is hard and we, as people, should do our best to remind others that we are enough, we are important, we have the power.. Enjoy your Monday folks! . <3

I remember growing up, almost every time we''d have a dentist appointment, my mom (Sherrie Pruett Wolfe) would schedule our (Austyn Ryan and I) appointments around lunch time or just before, so that when she picked us up from school for the appointment, it worked so that she could take us to Princess Gardens afterwards (our favorite Chinese restaurant) as a reward/tradition. Now, I take my lunch break time and the morning and afternoon breaks in between to cover the time I spent away from my desk crossing my fingers and hoping there''s no cavity or broken filling that''s going to cost me an arm and a leg. This, my friends, is part of being an adult...and while I care about my health, there is no longer a reward for good hygiene. Some of the little things don''t excite my adult brain like they did when I was just a girl still make for beautiful memories my mother has given me and the fun times I got to experience growing up are something I''ll never forget and will cherish forever. . With all that being said---Being an adult means getting to make your own decisions, having the freedom that has no limit and adventuring in all of the ways that make me feel happy, being my own guide is fun and I''m enjoying the ride just as much if not more! <3

Hi all. TL;DR - the customer service makes Drizly worth it. . I don‚Äôt usually do the promo thing but tonight‚Äôs experience sold me on this service. Met him, he passed me the bag and took off. Took three steps and just as I entered the lobby of my building the bag breaks and the St Germain and a bottle of wine fall out and shatter. Only then did I notice that the bag was wet so I got upset that it wasn‚Äôt me that screwed up but the delivery that caused me to lose $50+ of the delivery.. Left a 2-Star review and figured the experience was over, but Drizly reacted and, with the photo evidence of the shattered bottles, has sent out a replacement for both at no charge. Just got a notice that the replacements are 5 minutes out! . So, use @Drizly for your booze deliveries. I‚Äôm really impressed.

Our system is set up to place people in power who seek power. It isn''t merit, we don''t elevate people to authority by acclamation, they aren''t raised up from the population for their works and wisdom. No, we follow men and women who clawed and clambered and elbowed their way to the front, people who elevated themselves above others.. Is it any wonder, then, that they fail to exhibit ethics or morality that''s consistent with our expectations? Is it really a surprise that they''re rapists and pedophiles and theives? That they hold self interest above all else? It shouldn''t be a shock, this is what we endorse and participate in, subject only to the ritual of voting in which we choose one bad actor over another, differentiated only by the relative harm they have caused or are likely to cause. A broken system produces broken results, and we''re shocked by it, then do it all again anyway.

My high-effort chili failed to win the chili cook-off at work. It was still fun, always enjoy cooking.. I did everything scratch, and didn''t follow a recipe. It turned out really good, I think, but it didn''t pull down the votes. I had ground beef, venison, and steak; pinto, black, and red kidney beans, heirloom, roma, and cherry tomatoes, plus chili, chipotle , and cubanelle pepper.. Some lessons learned for next year:. * Chipotle chili blows out almost all subtly. I had three proteins in my chili, each cooked separately with different layers of flavor. You can''t taste any of it, because the chipotle blows it all out. I wanted the smokey flavor in there, so next time I''ll try a different approach to getting the smoke without covering up all the other depth.. * Al dente beans stay al dente in a crock pot. I left my beans slightly under on the theory that they would cook more in the crock pot on the day of the cook-off, leaving them perfect when the tasters came. Instead, my slightly-under beans stayed slightly under. I don''t mind it at all, but it isn''t what most tasters expect in chili, and may have been off-putting.. * The toppings don''t matter. I brought fresh avocado, sour cream, fresh chopped green onions, and Frito chips as adornments to my chili. Although it''s delicious to put all that on top, most tasters didn''t bother so it should not be a factor in the flavor profile.. * Start earlier. I started my chili around 8:00pm for the next day. It was fine, but I would have benefited from more hours to allow the spices to fully bloom. I detected some notes of raw spices in my chili that wouldn''t have been there had I allowed a longer cook time on the overall dish. Plus, that cook time might have finished my beans, giving a double benefit.. Next year, that apron will be mine!

The issue of gun violence won''t be solved by a law. As trite as it is, the counter-argument is true: people who break laws don''t care about laws. There are laws against murder, yet people commit murder.. The issue of gun violence isn''t about mental health. This is a cop-out -- mental illness is not inherently violent, and mental health treatment requires the active participation of the person being treated. Even if treatment were more readily available, which I agree it should be, if you don''t seek help it doesn''t really matter how available it is. Even if we had free mental healthcare in this country, it wouldn''t stop gun violence.. The problem is cultural. We''ve spent generations glorifying gun violence, and making heroes out of people who use guns in the name of the state. From soldiers to cops, we make games out of it, we make movies about it, we encourage our children into the professions. We idolize it, we glorify it. We embrace gun violence, in part because it''s the only way we can maintain our ethical and moral self-image as a people and live with the terrible harm our society causes to other people. We celebrate gun violence and those who perpetuate it because it''s a national trauma, and we are ultimately powerless to change it so we find ways to live with it. Our media, our entertainment, our very sense of heroism is wrapped around the good guy/bad guy dichotomy, solved with a bullet. The bullet has been with us since the creation of this country, and it''s built into our national ethos.. No law will change that. No mental health service will change that. We look for answers in every place but ourselves. If we do not accept gun violence, we must reject it at every level. Not just in a school shooting, but institutional violence, state violence, all violence. As long as we live in a society which endorses certain kinds of violence, we will always be forced to normalize and accept it, and we will always be victims of that violence because it lives in our culture. It isn''t a mental health issue. It isn''t a gun control issue. It''s a culture issue, it''s what we are willing and not willing to accept, under any justification. As long as we have the soldier and the cop, armed with a gun, justified in violence, we will see that violence reflected at every other level of our society. If we want to reject or replace that lifestyle, we have to do it at every level. Every level. That''s all of us.

Today I cut off and donated 17 inches of my hair in honor of my Aunt Tamie. It''s been 2 years and 2 days since she left this world and I still miss her everyday. My hair will be donated to the Pantene Beautiful Lengths program which provides real-hair wigs to women fighting cancer. I hope to help these brave women in their battle against cancer, however small the gesture may be. . Now to liven the mood a bit, here are some pros and cons to cutting my hair:. Pros:. I no longer have to buy gallons of shampoo and conditioner.. No longer will I suffocate on my own hair on windy days.. I no longer have to hold my hair to pee. (Yeap. That''s a thing). Cons:. I can''t use my own hair as a scarf anymore so I''ll have to invest in one of those.. I can''t jokingly hang myself with my own hair in long, drawn out meetings.. I love you Aunt Tamie, where ever you are. ‚ù§‚ù§‚ù§

Yesterday was pretty amazing, minus the car accident we were in before meeting my family (we are ok, just very sore). This is a photo we took after lunch at my birth parents persimmon farm. I learned many things about my family, their history, how savvy they are in business, life growing up, how they fell in love, so much - they are also very well respected in the community. This photo only has my birth parents and one siblings family as my other siblings were finishing up work for the day. Today we all leave together for Jeju Island. I feel like I am the luckiest girl, not only did I learn that my reunion was VERY unique as an adoptee from South Korea, but my family is really special. They are beautiful inside and out, the kindest, very loving, and also have a really great sense of humor!

all: i spent about 15 minutes with it (it''s my friend''s, and he will let me use it more i''m sure). The short version is it was a joy. Their website doesn''t do a great job of explaining it, but hopefully this image does. It has two robust multimode filter sections, but then an additional third spaced filter (LP/HP, BP/BP, etc) that you can feed the signal through for texture and harmonics. So think 2 main signal paths but then an additional one for movement or dynamics (e.g., super resonant velocity plucks on top of your main bass).. http://www.schmidt-synthesizer.com/images/gallery/schmidt_detail_07.jpg

I guess what I really loved about it was that in 15 minutes of tinkering (no manual or help) I easily knew how to do 90% of what it did. It feels like a synthesizer designed for people who love synthesizers. The only menu diving I had to do was to switch layers in multitimbral mode, and that was only 1 level deep. I kept mentally comparing it to the andromeda, where I everything required a mod button and an encoder turn, and 2 years of owning it i still got things wrong. But keep in mind this is a $20,000 synth, it's an art project / labor of love really.

Hey all, thanks for all the suggestions and feedback. We looked at Gliffy, Draw.io, Lucidchart, Sketchboard, and Cacoo. The winner was Lucidchart because it's the only one that nails multi-user collaboration. Draw.io is free, but a few things bugged us, especially the pseudo-google UI and ACLs that don't work very well. It looks exactly like a google product but doesn't work like one, and that confuses a distributed team who works on google docs + sheets with familiar functions all day. It seems like it's just in a holding pattern hoping for an Atlassian acquisition someday. Sketchboard is weird and too specialized to charge what they are charging for it. Gliffy and Lucidchart are nearly neck in neck featurewise and pricewise, but Lucidchart was just easier, has more templates, better collaboration, etc., so we went with that. In the end we needed a tool that our support team &  receptionists felt comfortable using instead of just the engineers, so usability and friendliness wins.

None of them saw past 10:00am Sept 11, 2001. In one single moment life may never be the same. As you live and enjoy the breaths you take today and tonight before you go to sleep in preparation for your life tomorrow, kiss the ones you love, snuggle a little tighter, and never take one second of your life for granted.. Rest in Peace, Pita Pounder Schiller. . March 13, 2003 - June 08, 2018. Although we only had the privilege of being your humans for the last three months, you brought a lot of joy and amusement to our lives. You always handled things on your terms, and we appreciated your strong, independent nature. You quickly settled into our pack, but you weren''t shy about letting the other dogs know if they were acting like fools.. We got a lot of laughs when you would deliberately take your treats and plop in front of the other dogs to savor them. If something (or someone) was in your way, you didn''t hesitate to pound on through to your destination. Until last week, we would get tired before you would when playing ball. Although your hearing and vision weren''t at full strength, that didn''t keep you from diving in the boxwood bushes to investigate rabbits and other suspicious interlopers. . We send many thanks to Kalamazoo Animal Rescue, Pita''s foster mom, Rebecca, and Rebecca''s family for taking such great care of Pita while under your care. Although we will always miss her, we are thankful that we got to be a part of her journey.. Rest easy, Pita.

This summer at a family get-to-gether, I offered to make my nephew a smash cake for his first birthday. Fast forward a weeks, and the smash cake turned in to a two tier cake for 40 people and cupcakes as an alternative. Considering I usually bake for only my family (who are easily wowed by my amateur baking skills), I was a little stressed over the situation and the potential of disappointing a room full of people (half of whom I didn''t know real well!) who were expecting bakery quality cake. This cake journey involved a test cake that completely altered the design of the cake, multiple days of baking, a quest to find a better frosting, learning how to support and stack a second layer, getting creative on how to transport said cake, and staying up until 2 am to complete everything because I threw my baking schedule off by making and testing out multiple frosting recipes on the night I was supposed to start frosting everything. Phew! But, in the end, it all worked out. The cake was delicious (thank you Betty Crocker! My next quest is to find a decent cake recipe made from scratch), the frosting was amazing (no, I didn''t find 'the one'" I''m looking for, but I did manage to find a new recipe I like quite a bit), and it made it safely to its destination in an upside down rubbermaid tote. Now, on to the next baking challenge..."

We had an exhausting summer - it started with our camper Dolly getting some repairs and a glamping makeover (she still needs her curtains updated, but there's only so much time in a day...), we became beekeepers, we spent weeks getting quotes to either add a room on our house or get a new roof, siding, and front porch extension; we recovered from a heart attack after getting above mentioned quotes; At some point (before or after? I think before) we squeezed in a quick camping trip to Fort Custer.  We decided to do the porch ourselves so we put a few weeks of sweat equity in to framing that out. We spent a few weekends yard-sale-ing (always a summer highlight!!) We decided we needed an above ground pool so we all agreed to forego birthday and Christmas gifts and treat ourselves to having that put in, but then found out our electric lines were in the way so we cancelled the pool; then realized we could move it over a few feet and still squeeze it in so we did that. Then on the install day the crew found an underground bee hive and stopped working because the only person who could drive the bobcat was dealthy allergic, then their truck stalled in our driveway, and then we didn't hear from them for a few days...but it eventually got put in, destroying our backyard and back deck in the process; (which is still a mess, but that's another project). We tried to go camping again but discovered frame issues with our truck (which we bought 6 months ago) that wasn't worth the money to fix. We bought another used truck and sold our other. We finished the porch by putting vinyl decking and railing on. Along the way we tried to turn our inside-turned-outside-because-he-kept-peeing-in-my-basement cat back in to an second-chance-at-living-inside-cat. That lasted about three weeks and he became an inside-turned-outside-turned-inside-turned-outside-again cat - he seems happier, my basement seems happier too. We helped a friend split and haul wood from his friend's recently cut down tree and then found more free wood in Elkhart that required two round trips - our front side yard is filled with wood that needs splitting or stacking still. We rounded this exhausting summer out with a nice long weekend up at Yankee Springs Recreation Area where we swam, boated, fished, swam some more, and enjoyed living around the campfire. It was a fast summer, an exhausting summer, but it was a great summer. How many more days till next summer!?!? with Benjamin Schrader
And we have 90% of a porch. Woot woot!! Totally worth the work.

Wow 10 years already?! Tony Bontrager took this picture of me when I took over the Junior Deacon''s spot at then Tyrian Lodge #718 with George Burkley''s prodding.  This was my first year as a Freemason and it was my first officer position in lodge.. Since then, I''ve gone through all of the officer chairs (one per year), helped oversee the move to Goshen, watched as we merged and became Tyrian Lodge #12, finished my Worshipful Master''s year in 2013 and with the help of everyone at the lodge was awarded the Grandmaster''s Award with High Distinction, one of only a handful of lodges that year.  And I''ve made many life long friends through this great organization.. After being Worshipful Master, I was the Venerable Master of the Knights of St. Andrew for the South Bend Valley of Scottish Rite in 2014.. The current chapter in my Masonic life is seeing me work my way through the 8 years of officer chairs in the South Bend Scottish Rite''s Consistory, where I am currently the 1st Lt. My coach, Frass, posted this earlier. I was like hey, catchy title... I''m down for a quick read over lunch. The truth of the article though is what really got me. A lot of people that I consider great friends at this point in my life I''ve found through training. If you are reading this, thank you, all of you make my life better every day..

So at the behest of my Coach, I went and watched the 5th Episode of Fight World on Netflix. I was expecting something technical or useful for my training, but what I got was so much more. They talked about why they fight, why they train, and how it affects them. They don''t fight for glory or ego, they fight to survive. Something most of us don''t think about. The biggest eye opener for me though, was that they really drove home the point about how fighting brings people from all different cultures/religions/backgrounds and while you are training you see none of that. When you train, you only see a person, you have no fear or hate, you and your training partner are only there to make each other better. You grow together or you don''t grow at all. . I''ve seen these things even in my gym here in the states. We all have different political views, we are different races and sexes. But we all train together to push each other to be a better version of ourselves.. My favorite times are specifically after a brutal night of chokes or sparring, when you look at each other in the eye, and even though you literally just beat the shit out of each other for an hour, you smile, laugh, fist bump, and get right back to being friends. Better friends than you were before, because fighting brings people closer together.

This morning as I headed to campus I felt anxiety as I considered the safety of students, staff, faculty, and myself. . I felt gratitude for the law enforcement officers at CU, in Colorado, and across the country working to keep us safe. . I felt relief in the early afternoon when I learned there was no longer an immediate (known) threat. . And then I was left with overwhelming sadness. Sadness for a troubled young person. Sadness for our schools. Sadness for our country. Sadness for humanity.. Tomorrow is a new day, and likely some of my optimism will return; but tonight, I sit with sadness.
